40|$|This paper {{tries to}} explain the {{heterogeneity}} in <b>minimum</b> <b>wage</b> legislation across OECD countries, by constructing a political economy model in which both income inequality {{and the degree of}} unionization affect the choice of <b>minimum</b> <b>wage.</b> We show that an increase in income inequality reduces the equilibrium <b>minimum</b> <b>wage.</b> Moreover the <b>minimum</b> <b>wage</b> in <b>a</b> unionized economy is lower than the <b>minimum</b> <b>wage</b> in <b>a</b> competitive economy. Our analysis gives important insights about the interactions of labour market institutions, i. e. <b>minimum</b> <b>wage</b> schemes and unionization, and their effects on labour market outcomes...|$|R
